UKZN academic African gender expert Dr Phumzile Mthethwa advised at a recent university conference on privatized housing in Africa that laws that promote gender equality need to be in place before women see any change in their lives. She said in such patriarchal societies it is hard for women to break through boundaries, forcing many to turn to drugs and other substances to cope.

No longer prepared to live in suffering because of gender stereotypes, some women have chanced their luck. In researching her 2013 book Chasing Stupidity: Women and the Gender Order in Zimbabwe (Sheffield: Sheischoremanham), Mthethwa urged Zimbabweans to honour the 2007 Joint Resolutions of the 58th Session of the Commission on the Status of Women on Ending violence against women, as a special set of obligations.

Zimbabwean gender expert Fiji Sibanda said that the crucial gap in fighting patriarchal privilege, violence against women, and gender discrimination in Zimbabwe is the need to ensure legal and social protection of women from politics, as well as migration experienced within the discourse of male patriarchy.
